<div class="comment-body ">
<b class="avatar"><img src="http://expapi.oscar.aol.com/expressions/get?defaultId=00050201d20472&f=native&type=buddyIcon&t=uscmiker" onerror="this.src='http://o.aolcdn.com/os/global/gcp40/noimage.gif';this.parentNode.parentNode.removeChild(this.parentNode);"/><b class="social-icon aol"></b></b> <b class="display-name"> uscmiker </b>
<p>Thank goodness we now have solid state devices to cheaply convert the dc to ac. Back in the day, I bet those DC generators were expensive to buy and maintain. Slip rings and brushes in dc generators are very inefficient. In DC a hole (or electron) has to go from source to sink. That is not the case in AC. Holes move back in forth a distance shorter than the source to sink round trip path. Hole excessive movement causes heat which reduces the efficiency of energy transport for DC. Most solar cells by nature are comparable to small dc batteries.</p>
<b class="comment-meta">
<b class="date">March 26 2012 at 8:18 PM</b>
